04663nam a22006615i 9780292748699DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212013txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927486997 a10.7560/7486822doi  a(DE-B1597)587033  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aKGD2501b.C37 2013 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a364.3/740899742072812231 aCarey, David, David, Jr., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aI Ask for Justice :bMaya Women, Dictators, and Crime in Guatemala, 1898–1944 /cDavid, Jr. Carey, David. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations, Maps, and Tables -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: -- t1. Dictators, Indígenas, and the Legal System: Intersections of Race and Crime -- t2. “Rough and Thorny Terrain”: Moonshine, Gender, and Ethnicity -- t3. “Productive Activity”: Female Vendors and Ladino Authorities in the Market -- t4. Unnatural Mothers and Reproductive Crimes: Infanticide, Abortion, and Cross-Dressing -- t5. Wives in Danger and Dangerous Women: Domestic and Female Violence -- t6. Honorable Subjects: Public Insults, Family Feuds, and State Power -- tConclusion: Emboldened and Constrained -- tAppendices -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGiven Guatemala’s record of human rights abuses, its legal system has often been portrayed as illegitimate and anemic. I Ask for Justice challenges that perception by demonstrating that even though the legal system was not always just, rural Guatemalans considered it a legitimate arbiter of their grievances and an important tool for advancing their agendas. As both a mirror and an instrument of the state, the judicial system simultaneously illuminates the limits of state rule and the state’s ability to co-opt Guatemalans by hearing their voices in court. Against the backdrop of two of Latin America’s most oppressive regimes—the dictatorships of Manuel Estrada Cabrera (1898–1920) and General Jorge Ubico (1931–1944)—David Carey Jr. explores the ways in which indigenous people, women, and the poor used Guatemala’s legal system to manipulate the boundaries between legality and criminality. Using court records that are surprisingly rich in Maya women’s voices, he analyzes how bootleggers, cross-dressers, and other litigants crafted their narratives to defend their human rights. Revealing how nuances of power, gender, ethnicity, class, and morality were constructed and contested, this history of crime and criminality demonstrates how Maya men and women attempted to improve their socioeconomic positions and to press for their rights with strategies that ranged from the pursuit of illicit activities to the deployment of the legal system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMaya womenxCrimes againstzGuatemalaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMaya womenxLegal status, laws, etc.zGuatemalaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMaya womenzGuatemalaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aSex discrimination in criminal justice administrationzGuatemalaxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aPiccato, Pablo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/74868240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292748699423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292748699/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK